# Bolna → Slack Alert Integration

Sends a Slack message whenever a Bolna voice call ends, including:
- Call `id`
- `agent_id`
- `duration` (seconds)
- `transcript`

---

## How It Works

```
Bolna call ends
  → Bolna POSTs webhook payload to your server (/webhook/bolna)
    → server filters for status = "completed"
      → server sends formatted Slack message via Incoming Webhook
```

---

## Setup

### 1. Slack — Create an Incoming Webhook

1. Go to https://api.slack.com/apps → **Create New App** → From scratch
2. Name it (e.g. `Bolna Alerts`), select your workspace
3. Left sidebar → **Incoming Webhooks** → toggle **On**
4. Click **Add New Webhook to Workspace**, choose a channel
5. Copy the webhook URL

### 2. Server — Install & Run

```bash
npm install
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env and paste your Slack webhook URL
node server.js
```

Your server starts at `http://localhost:3000`.

### 3. Expose Your Server to the Internet

Bolna needs to reach your server publicly. Use **ngrok** for local testing:

```bash
npx ngrok http 3000
# Copy the https://xxxx.ngrok.io URL
```

For production, deploy to Railway (recommended), Render, Fly.io, or any Node.js host.

Railway quick deploy:
1. Create a new project at https://railway.app
2. Connect your GitHub repo or push your code
3. In Railway, add an environment variable named `SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL` and set it to your Slack Incoming Webhook URL (Settings → Variables)
4. Ensure `package.json` has a start script, e.g.:

```json
"scripts": {
  "start": "node server.js"
}
```

5. Deploy — Railway will provide a public HTTPS URL. Use:

```
https://<your-railway-url>/webhook/bolna
```

Note: Railway provides a public HTTPS URL; if the URL changes update the webhook in the Bolna dashboard. Also confirm the environment variable is set in Railway so the server can post to Slack.

### 4. Configure Bolna Agent Webhook

**Option A — Dashboard (easiest):**
1. Log in at https://platform.bolna.ai
2. Open your agent (or clone template `d311e737-70e6-4075-bef6-c0ef3a7026b4`)
3. Go to the **Analytics Tab**
4. Paste your URL in **"Push all execution data to webhook"**:
   `https://your-server.com/webhook/bolna`
5. Click **Save agent**

**Option B — API:**
```bash
curl -X PATCH https://api.bolna.ai/v2/agent/<YOUR_AGENT_ID> \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer <BOLNA_API_KEY>" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"webhook_url": "https://your-server.com/webhook/bolna"}'
```

---

## Webhook Payload Reference

Bolna sends this on every status change. We only act on `status = "completed"`.

```json
{
  "id": 7432382142914,
  "agent_id": "3c90c3cc-0d44-4b50-8888-8dd25736052a",
  "status": "completed",
  "transcript": "Agent: Hello...\nUser: Hi...",
  "conversation_time": 123,
  "telephony_data": {
    "duration": 42,
    "to_number": "+10123456789",
    "from_number": "+1987654007"
  }
}
```

The server extracts:
| Field | Source in payload |
|---|---|
| `id` | `body.id` |
| `agent_id` | `body.agent_id` |
| `duration` | `body.telephony_data.duration` (falls back to `conversation_time`) |
| `transcript` | `body.transcript` |

---

## IP Whitelist

Bolna sends webhooks from: `13.203.39.153`  
Whitelist this IP in your firewall/security group.

---

## Testing Locally

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/webhook/bolna \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "id": 12345,
    "agent_id": "d311e737-70e6-4075-bef6-c0ef3a7026b4",
    "status": "completed",
    "transcript": "Agent: Hello, how can I help?\nUser: I need support.",
    "telephony_data": { "duration": 67 }
  }'
```

You should see a Slack message appear in your channel immediately.